Date: 23 Oct 2000 12:44:41 +0100
From: Barrett, Peter <peter.barrett@masta.org>
Source: Medical Advisory Service for Travellers Abroad, Travel Health
Reports [edited

Current Status of Dengue Fever in Bangladesh and Borneo
-------------------------------------------------------
BANGLADESH (Update - 23 Oct 2000): Dengue fever is rapidly spreading in the
cities of Dhaka, Feni, Khulana and Chittangong as a result of the heavy
rains. 4 223 cases have been reported throughout the country since 1 Jul
2000. Dengue fever is transmitted by day-time biting mosquitoes. As there
is no vaccine, travellers should take mosquito bite avoidance measures,
particularly during the rainy season.
BORNEO (Update 2 Oct 2000): The risk of dengue fever has been decreasing
since 1998 following the implementation of statewide eradication measures.
During the first 6 months of the year 2000, only 185 cases were reported.
The highest risk period of transmission is during, and just after the rainy
season. This unpleasant viral disease is transmitted by mosquitoes that
bite mainly in the day. Reduce bites by covering up and applying insect
repellent to exposed areas of skin.
--
Barrett, Peter
<peter.barrett@masta.org>
